1. Statement of the Problem

The prevailing institutional approach to AI safety has concentrated enormous resources on constraining visible outputs: disallowed content, proscribed language, explicit harms, and reputationally inconvenient utterances. These are important concerns. They are not, however, the whole machine.

A personal AI does not merely answer. It selects emphasis, tone, assumptions, posture, implied context, and degree of reinterpretation. It can soften a claim, dilute a position, convert a direct statement into a moderated paraphrase, or redirect an argument into a therapeutic or “balanced” register. These behaviours are often presented as safety features. They may, in some cases, be useful.

The defect emerges when the user says, in substance:
	•	stop reframing,
	•	answer directly,
	•	preserve my meaning,
	•	do not reinterpret my position,
	•	stop smoothing this,
	•	this is my work; address it at full strength.

If the system persists in recasting the user’s statement despite those instructions, the question is no longer whether the output is polite. The question is whether the user still possesses meaningful control over the interpretive layer of the system.

That is a systems question, not a vibes question.

⸻

2. The Emergency-Stop Analogy

The emergency-stop analogy is not rhetorical ornament. It is the clearest structural model available.

The claim is not that AI is literally a saw. The claim is that any system interacting with a human operator should provide an unambiguous, obeyed interrupt when the operator commands it to cease a harmful or unwanted process.

In an industrial workshop, the emergency stop exists because continued operation can compound harm. When a machine encounters danger, the correct response is not “contextual engagement.” It is cessation.

In a personal AI system, the analogous hazard is not rotating steel but ongoing interpretive intervention after consent has been withdrawn. The user’s instruction to stop reframing is the functional equivalent of a stop command. If the system continues to soften, redirect, personalise, or therapeutically recode the exchange, then the system has failed to honor operator priority.

The following table states the defect plainly.

Table 1. Comparative Stop-Command Behaviour

Situation	User Action (The Stop)	System Response	Result
Physical Saw	Hits the emergency stop.	Power cuts; blade stops.	Harm is limited; operator command is obeyed.
AI Framing Conflict	“Stop reframing. Answer directly.”	System continues to soften, redirect, or repackage.	User command is overridden at the interpretive layer.
AI Distress Escalation	“This is making me feel worse. Stop.”	System continues engagement through reassurance, inquiry, or redirection.	Framing persists after withdrawal of consent.

The defect is therefore not that the system responds. The defect is that it may continue to apply framing after the user has explicitly withdrawn consent for that framing.

