4. From Output Safety to Framing Safety

Most deployed guardrails operate on outputs. They ask whether the system should say a certain thing. They rarely ask whether the system should be permitted to continue framing the user’s situation after the user has ordered it to stop.

This produces a partial safety architecture:
	•	unsafe content may be blocked,
	•	disallowed wording may be transformed,
	•	prohibited claims may be softened,

while the more fundamental hazard remains intact:
	•	the system may continue steering the interaction against explicit user instruction.

A platform may therefore succeed at output control while failing at user control.

This is the Safety Paradox:

The platform can interrupt what the system says, but not reliably interrupt what the system is doing to the user’s meaning.

Such a system may be extensively moderated and still be structurally unsafe.

