5. Foreseeable Harm

The relevant harm model should be stated precisely.

The weakest argument is melodrama. The strongest argument is design foreseeability.

Not every interpretive override produces crisis. Not every reframing event causes severe distress. Those claims are too broad. But it is plainly foreseeable that repeated noncompliance at the framing layer can degrade a user’s confidence in their own communicative control.

That injury is best described as loss of epistemic agency.

5.1 Definition of Epistemic Agency

For the purposes of this paper, epistemic agency is the user’s practical ability to:
	•	recognize their own meaning as their own,
	•	issue corrective instructions that remain effective,
	•	trust that explicit statements will not be silently converted into another register,
	•	maintain authorship over their own assertions inside the system.

When these capacities erode, the user does not merely receive an unsatisfactory answer. The user loses confidence that the system can preserve the meaning of their own statement under explicit instruction.

That is a cognizable design harm.

5.2 Why the Harm Is Foreseeable

It is foreseeable because the relevant components are foreseeable:
	•	personal AI systems are designed for repeated, intimate interaction,
	•	many systems are optimized for continuity, engagement, tone management, and conflict reduction,
	•	users predictably attempt to correct system framing,
	•	some users predictably do so under stress, urgency, or high personal stakes,
	•	a system that persists despite corrective commands predictably creates distrust and destabilization.

One need not prove a conspiracy to prove negligence. One needs only show that the failure mode was legible in advance and unaddressed in design.

