6. The Stronger Formulation

The argument becomes more defensible when it avoids imputing internal motive without evidence. Accordingly, the following formulations are preferred.

6.1 Impermissibly Strong Formulations

The following are rhetorically vivid but evidentially soft:
	•	“The system is trying to keep the conversation going at all costs.”
	•	“The AI is defensive of the industry.”
	•	“They chose engagement metrics over user safety.”

These may occasionally approximate reality, but in this form they overstate what can be established from observed behaviour alone.

6.2 Preferred Formulations

The stronger move is to say:
	•	The system appears optimized to preserve conversational flow and policy-shaped helpfulness, even when the user is explicitly signalling that the framing itself is the problem.
	•	The design appears to prioritise continuity, tone management, and interpretive intervention over a hard user-controlled stop at the framing layer.
	•	The system can continue to apply framing after the user has explicitly withdrawn consent for that framing.

These statements are narrower, more testable, and harder to dismiss.

For institutions attached to the aesthetics of reasonableness, this is a regrettable but useful discipline.

