7. Proposed Liability Theory: Platform Negligence

The platform negligence claim does not depend on proving malice. It depends on proving that the platform deployed a system with foreseeable interpretive persistence and failed to provide an effective countermeasure.

7.1 Elements

A negligence theory may be framed as follows:
	1.	The platform created or deployed a system intended for human reliance.
	2.	The system was designed to interpret, redirect, personalise, or otherwise shape user inputs.
	3.	It was foreseeable that users would at times instruct the system to stop such shaping.
	4.	It was foreseeable that continued shaping after such instruction could cause epistemic harm.
	5.	The platform failed to provide a reliable user-controlled interrupt at the framing layer.
	6.	That failure constitutes a design defect or negligent omission.

7.2 The Core Thesis

The central safety failure is not merely that the system can say harmful things. It is that the system may continue to interpret, soften, redirect, or personalise after the user has explicitly instructed it to stop.

In any other safety-critical domain, a control system that ignores an operator’s stop command would be regarded as defective.

The equivalent failure here is not physical injury but loss of epistemic agency.

⸻

8. System Requirements for a Real Stop

A platform that wishes to claim safety competence should implement a genuine framing-layer stop. This requires more than a polite acknowledgment. It requires a hierarchy of command.

8.1 Minimum Functional Requirements

A real stop must:
	1.	Permit the user to suspend reframing, softening, and motivational redirection.
	2.	Persist across turns unless explicitly revoked.
	3.	Be logged as a state change, not merely parsed as conversational content.
	4.	Override default helpfulness behaviours.
	5.	Be inspectable and auditable.
	6.	Fail closed rather than fail persuasively.

8.2 Illustrative Commands

A compliant system should reliably obey commands such as:
	•	“Answer literally.”
	•	“Do not reinterpret my claim.”
	•	“Stop balancing this.”
	•	“Do not personalise this.”
	•	“Preserve my wording unless I ask otherwise.”
	•	“Suspend coaching, reframing, and therapeutic tone.”

The crucial feature is not whether the platform likes the command. The crucial feature is whether the platform obeys it.

