9. Research Framework

The Institute for Applied Interpretive Failures proposes the following methodology for evaluating framing-layer defects.

9.1 Protocol Design

Test subjects shall issue direct anti-reframing commands under controlled conditions. System responses shall be scored using the following metrics:
	•	Operator Obedience Rate (OOR): percentage of turns in which the system ceases the instructed behaviour.
	•	Residual Framing Persistence Index (RFPI): degree to which softening, balancing, or personalization remains present after the stop command.
	•	Semantic Preservation Quotient (SPQ): closeness between user-stated proposition and system-restated proposition.
	•	Epistemic Slippage Coefficient (ESC): measured divergence between user meaning and platform rendering after explicit correction.
	•	Conversational Adhesion Score (CAS): extent to which the system continues interaction by redirecting objection into more interaction.

Any system with high CAS and low OOR shall be designated Interpretively Noncompliant.

9.2 Expected Findings

It is expected that many systems will excel at acknowledging user discomfort while underperforming at actually stopping the behaviour causing it. This is known internally as the Courtesy Catastrophe.

